            <biogHist> 
                <abstract>Little is known of Sarah Paul's early life. She came to the attention of the public after being discovered by her neighbours to be a woman in 1760. At that time she had been married to Mary Parlour for about 6 months. She was charged with 'defrauding a young woman of money and apparel, by marrying her' but as Mary did not appear at court the case could go no further. It is reported that Sarah died around 1766 in a St. Sepulchre's workhouse.</abstract>
                <citation>Derry, Caroline. “‘Female Husbands’, Community and Courts in the Eighteenth Century.” The Journal of Legal History 38, no. 1 (2017): 41–82. https://doi.org/10.1080/01440365.2017.1289674.</citation>
            </biogHist>         
